    </exercise>
    <exercise id="fs-id2653513" type="problems-exercises"><problem id="fs-id2017413">
      <para id="import-auto-id1568977">You can sometimes find deep red crystal vases in antique stores, called uranium glass because their color was produced by doping the glass with uranium. Look up the natural isotopes of uranium and their half-lives, and calculate the activity of such a vase assuming it has 2.00 g of uranium in it. Neglect the activity of any daughter nuclides.</para>
    </problem></exercise>

    <exercise id="fs-id2440734" type="problems-exercises"><problem id="fs-id3033800">
      <para id="import-auto-id2682213">A tree falls in a forest. How many years must pass before the <m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:msup><m:mrow/><m:mtext>14</m:mtext></m:msup><m:mtext>C</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{"" lSup { size 8{"14"} } C} {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> activity in 1.00 g of the tree’s carbon drops to 1.00 decay per hour?</para></problem>
